{"title":"Semantic Knowledge Distillation for Onboard Satellite Earth Observation Image Classification","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"Knowledge distillation for Earth observation image classification often relies on a single teacher or fixed teacher weights, which can be unstable and suboptimal when teacher reliability varies across inputs. There is a need to adaptively leverage multiple teachers so the student prioritizes reliable guidance per instance.","method":"Propose DualKD: a dual-teacher distillation framework with dynamic confidence-based weighting. Teacher confidences are computed as the average of the maximum probabilities from temperature-softened outputs. Weights (α, β) are adapted using a threshold δ and a minimum weight w_min: ignore both teachers if both confidences are very low; downweight the less-confident teacher if one is low; use equal weights when both are confident. The KD loss is a weighted sum of KL divergences (scaled by τ^2) between the student and each teacher, combined with cross-entropy on ground-truth labels. On EuroSAT, DualKD outperforms single-teacher KD for ResNet8 (92.88% accuracy vs. 91.77/91.06) and ResNet16 (96.46% vs. 94.49/93.29)."},{"problem":"Onboard satellite processing is resource-constrained (compute, memory, power), yet requires accurate real-time image classification. Powerful ViTs perform well but are too heavy for deployment on such platforms.","method":"Distill semantic knowledge from two strong ViT teachers (EfficientViT and MobileViT) into lightweight ResNet students (ResNet8/ResNet16) using DualKD. This yields deployable models with high accuracy while drastically reducing resource demands. ResNet8 exceeds 90% accuracy/precision/recall and, compared to ViT teachers, reduces parameters by ~97.5–97.8%, FLOPs by up to 96.7%, inference time by up to 63.5%, and power consumption by up to 86.2%, making it suitable for onboard EO applications."}]}
